description.narrative:
The achievements of the past programme will act as foundation of the next three year advocacy work. In principal, the program will aim for the following goals: a) improving organizational capacity and economic independence of artisanal fishers; b) stimulate and initiate policy reform and c) to strengthen the capacity of the network and the network members to stimulate and enlarge public support on fishery justice in Indonesia.

Closely related to the advocacy work and policy reform effort of the network, KIARA has seen a growing government emphasis to encourage industrialisation of the fisheries sector, both in capture fisheries and aquaculture. This is in line with the findings of the evaluation, that stated, “Overtime, KIARA has seen that marine and fisheries affairs are not mere domestic issues, but have escalated and cannot be isolated from the global fish market dynamics”.  In this line, the network strives for the rights and concerns of small scale fishers and small scale fish farmers to be well represented in national policy and laws. These state instruments should protect the interest of these vulnerable groups to be able to sustain their livelihood, to secure domestic fish supplies as well as to be empowered and may take part and benefit from the market opportunities, i.e. through fishers cooperatives and producer groups.

KIARA's programme 2011-2014 will be geared towards three lines of objectives:

1. Improve the organizational capacity and economic independence of artisanal fisherfolks;
Target: By March 2014, (1) KIARA has documented and promoted at least four initiatives of cooperation among fellow fishers organizations in order to achieve economic independence, through: sharing of resources, sharing of creative technology, sharing ofpotential market, and, sharing of knowledge, (2 ) at least 5 traditional fishers organization is formally involved in the preparation of fisheries policy, (3) at least 1.000 persons in artisanal fisherycommunity (50% of women) participating in coastal protection training, (4) at least there are 3 of  Fish Auction Place (TPI) (whichhave been intervened by KIARA) can perform its functions to serve and protect the interests of artisanal fisherfolks;

2. Stimulateand initiate policy reforms to support the realization of fishery justice;
Target: By March 2013, (1) KIARA has actively stimulatedthe effort to revise two national and three provincial/ district-level policies to ensure the fishery justice initiatives, (2) KIARA has 2 fisheries policy papersfor policy intervention at the regional/ international level; (3) KIARA stimulating and mainstreaminga new law related to protection of artisanal fishers: Draft on the Act of Protection and Empowerment of Fishers ;

3. Optimize KIARA role as a coalition organization that is able to stimulate and enlarge public support on fishery justice initiative in Indonesia;
Target: By March 2014, (1) all the components of KIARA (members/presidiums/ the secretariat) can execute the new mandate of the 4th GA of KIARA,(2) all the members of KIARA get capacity improvement and  practice them at regional level  advocacy, (3) at least 2 strategic networks at  national level and 2 strategic networks at the regional / international level establish collaboration with KIARAin supporting the fishery justice initiatives, (4) at least, 1,000 people (instead of fishing communities and victims) involved in KIARA campaign; (5) at least 1,000 people take advantage of and obtain information on fishery and marine policies by KIARA built in a day.

The detailed activities are represented in Annex 2 Indicator Table for the period of April 2011-March 2014.
